CHAPTER 5: CONVERGENCE
MAT
I haven't slept.
It's 6 AM. I've been sitting on my bed for two hours, staring at the duffel bag in my closet. Fifteen thousand dollars in cash. Property records. Tenant lists. Evidence of crimes I don't fully understand yet.
And blood on my hands.
Not literally. I didn't kill anyone last night. But I hurt people. Broke bones. Fired a gun. Worked with two strangers to rob a criminal and fight our way out like it was a fucking action movie.
My father's watch sits on my desk. I pick it up. Hold it. The weight feels heavier today.
"Stay clean, mijo. Don't end up like the other kids."
Sorry, Dad. Too late.
My door opens. Isa's standing there in her sleep clothes, hair messy, eyes sharp.
"You didn't come home until four AM."
"Job ran late."
"What kind of job, Mat?"
I can't answer. Just grab my keys.
"Mat—"
"I'm handling it, Isa."
"That's not an answer."
I brush past her. She doesn't stop me. Just watches me leave with that look on her face—the one that says she knows I'm lying and she's already grieving.

My phone rings as I'm leaving the building.
Cisco.
Fuck.
I answer. "Qué pedo." (What's up.)
"Hermano. Where's my cut?"
"It got complicated."
Silence. Then: "Complicated how? You got the stuff or not?"
"I got it. But there were... other people there."
"What OTHER people?"
"I don't know. Two guys. Professionals. We had to fight our way out together."
Long pause. I can hear him breathing. Angry breathing.
"And you just... worked with them? Without knowing who they are?"
"It was work with them or die. I chose option one."
"You owe me, Mat. That was MY job. MY territory. I set that up. You were supposed to be in and out, bring me the files, get your money. Not team up with random fucking strangers."
"I'm meeting them today. I'll figure out who they are, what they want. Then we talk."
"You got until tonight." His voice is ice now. "Or we got a problem. And you don't want problems with me, hermano. Not in this neighborhood."
He hangs up.
I stand there in the morning sun. Trapped between Cisco on one side and two guys I don't know on the other.
And I still don't know what I've stepped into.

I text the number from last night.
Noon. Griffith Park Observatory. Come alone or I disappear.
The response comes immediately.
We'll be there.
I spend the morning at the garage with the Mustang. Don't start it. Just sit inside. Hands on the wheel. Thinking.
Last night I crossed a line. The kind you don't come back from.
But maybe I've been on the wrong side of the line my whole life. Maybe the line was bullshit to begin with.
Dad followed the rules. Worked hard. Stayed clean.
They killed him anyway.
At eleven, I leave for Griffith Park. Get there early. Watch the parking lot. Make sure they're not setting a trap.
At 11:50, they arrive. Two guys. The older one—maybe early forties, moves like ex-military or ex-cop. The younger one—late thirties, walks like he owns the world even though he looks like he hasn't slept in a month.
They scan the area. Professional. Careful.
I step out from behind a pillar.
"Took you long enough."

COLE
The kid's been here since eleven. I can tell. He's positioned himself with clear sightlines, multiple exit routes. Smart.
"You said noon," I say. "It's noon."
"I've been here since eleven. Watching. Making sure you didn't bring friends."
Ray's next to me, silent. He's been silent all morning. Ever since I told him.
The kid notices. "What's wrong with you?"
Ray doesn't answer.
"Bullshit. You look like you've seen a ghost."
"Nothing," Ray manages.
I step between them. "Let's talk. You want to know who we are. We want to know who you are. Fair trade."
The kid studies us. Then nods toward a quieter spot away from tourists.
We follow.

We sit on a bench overlooking the city. LA sprawls below us—endless, ugly, beautiful, broken.
"You first," the kid says. "Who are you and why were you hitting Delgado?"
Might as well rip the band-aid off.
"My name's Cole Brennan. I work for Vincent Harlan. Or I did. Now I'm taking him apart."
The kid's expression shifts. "Vincent Harlan? The Broker?"
"You know him?"
"I know he owns my building. I know rent keeps going up and the heat doesn't work and my mom works two jobs and still can't afford her insulin." His voice is hard. Controlled. "I know families are getting evicted so he can 'reposition' properties. I know he's a fucking vulture."
I take a breath. This is going to go badly.
"I processed that building. Four years ago. Made the purchase look legitimate so Vincent could own it."
He stares at me.
"You what?"
"I launder money for Vincent. Real estate, shell companies, fake transactions. I've been doing it for six years. Your building?" I meet his eyes. "I made that happen."
The kid stands up fast. Hand goes to his pocket.
"So you're telling me my family's been trapped in that shithole because of YOU?"
"Yes."
"And now you want me to help you take him down? After you helped him TRAP us?"
"I'm not asking you to help. I'm offering you a chance to get revenge on the system that's been bleeding your family for four years."
He laughs. Bitter. Angry. "Revenge. From the guy who built the cage."
Ray finally speaks. "He's not the only one."

MAT
I look at the older guy. Ray. He's been quiet this whole time. Staring at the ground like he's waiting for it to swallow him.
"What?"
"Your name. Navarro. I knew I recognized it."
Something cold crawls up my spine. "How?"
He takes a breath. Can barely get the words out.
"Ricardo Navarro. Traffic stop. Eight years ago. South LA."
Everything stops.
"I was there."
The world tilts.
"What did you say?"
"I was there. I was a cop. My partner pulled him over. Your father reached for his wallet. And my partner shot him. Six times. And I stood there. And I watched. And I did NOTHING."
I can't breathe.
Can't move.
Can't think.
"You watched them kill my father."
"Yes."
"And you did nothing."
"Yes."
My hand goes to my pocket. The gun I took last night. I pull it out. Point it at his chest.
Cole tenses but doesn't move.
Ray doesn't flinch. Just sits there. Waiting.
"Why?"
"Because I was a coward. I was three years on the force. My partner was senior. He said your father reached for something, he feared for his life, it was clean. And I... I went along with it."
My hand's shaking. "You could have stopped him."
"I could have."
"You could have told the truth."
"I could have."
"But you didn't."
"No. I didn't." He looks at me now. First time. Eyes red. Haunted. "I filed the false report. I testified it was justified. I buried it. And I've been dying inside ever since."
"Good." My finger's on the trigger. "Now you can die outside too."
Cole speaks. "Mat. Don't."
"Give me one reason."
"Because if you shoot him here, you go to prison. And your mom and sister lose you too. Is that what your father would want?"
"Don't talk about my father."
"I'm not. I'm talking about your family. The ones still alive. The ones who need you."
"He deserves to die."
Ray's voice is quiet. "You're right. I do."
"Then why are you here? Why are you helping take down Vincent?"
"Because maybe... maybe if I can destroy the system that killed your father, that destroyed me, that's trapping your family... maybe that's worth something. Maybe I can do one good thing before I die."
"That doesn't bring him back."
"No. It doesn't. Nothing will."
I stand there. Gun aimed at his chest. My father's killer. Right here. Right in front of me.
I could pull the trigger.
Should pull the trigger.
But then what? Prison? Mom and Isa alone? Everything Dad sacrificed for nothing?
Tourists laugh in the distance. Kids running. Families. Normal people living normal lives.
And here I am pointing a gun at a broken man who wants to die.
"If I ever see you hesitate," I say slowly. "If I ever think you're not giving everything to burn Vincent down. I will kill you. You understand?"
"I understand."
"I'm not doing this for you. I'm doing this because my family's drowning and Vincent's the one holding us under."
I lower the gun. Slowly.
"But if you fuck me over. If you put my family in danger. You're dead."
"Fair."

COLE
Crisis averted. For now.
I pull out the files from Delgado's safe. Spread them on the bench.
"Now that we've got that settled. Let's talk about what we're actually doing."
Mat looks at the files. Property records. Addresses. Cash flow statements. Names.
"This is... a lot."
"This is one guy. Delgado managed twenty buildings. Vincent has dozens like him. Property managers, corrupt cops, lawyers, accountants. A whole network." I light a cigarette. "And I know all of them because I've been processing their money for six years."
Ray leans forward. "We hit them one by one. Learn more about Vincent's operations. Gather evidence. Take resources."
"And when we've got enough?" I tap the files. "We expose everything. Destroy him."
Mat crosses his arms. "Three people against an empire."
"Three people who know how the empire works. I know the money. Ray knows the law enforcement side. And you—" I look at him. "You're a ghost. Best infiltration specialist I've seen. You got into Delgado's safe in under a minute."
"So what? We just... keep robbing Vincent's people?"
"We dismantle his network. Piece by piece. Until there's nothing left."
"And then what? We all die?"
Ray almost smiles. "Probably."
"Great sales pitch."
I crush out the cigarette. "I'm not selling anything. I'm offering you a chance to fight back. You're already in this. Cisco knows you were there last night. Delgado's guys might not have seen our faces, but they know someone hit them. Vincent's going to be looking. You can run and hide, or you can fight."
Long silence.
Mat looks at the city below. Then at the files. Then at us.
"What's the next target?"
I allow myself a small smile.
"Detective Marcus Webb. Corrupt cop. Does pickups for Vincent, moves evidence, buries cases. Been on the payroll for ten years."
Ray's voice is hard. "I know him. Piece of shit. Testified against me in my investigation. Helped bury my career."
"He's our next hit. Friday night. I'll text you the details."
Mat stands. Looks at Ray one more time.
"I meant what I said. You hesitate, you're dead."
"I know."
"Good."
He looks at both of us.
"I'm not doing this because I trust you. I'm doing this because I'm tired of being a victim. My family's tired. My neighborhood's tired. It's time someone fought back."
"Then we fight."
No handshakes. No promises. Just a nod.
An understanding.
Mat walks away first. Then Ray. Then me.
Separate directions.
But moving toward the same target.

I sit in my car. Light another cigarette.
Three broken people. One impossible mission.
Vincent Harlan has no idea what's coming.
My phone buzzes. Text from an unknown number.
The Koreatown property closed successfully. Mr. Harlan is very pleased. He looks forward to continuing your productive relationship. -V
I delete it.
Not for long, Vincent.
Not for long.

VINCENT
The office is silent except for the hum of the air conditioning.
I'm looking at a map of Los Angeles. Red pins mark every property I own. Every business. Every operation.
Forty-seven buildings through various LLCs. Twelve legitimate businesses. Eight elected officials on payroll. Twenty-three police officers. Five judges.
Twenty years of building an empire.
My phone rings.
"Yes?"
"Sir." It's Marcus Delgado. He sounds nervous. Never a good sign. "We have a problem."
"Go on."
"My storage unit was hit last night. Someone took the records. Property files, cash, everything."
I set down my coffee. "How many people?"
"Three. My guys said they were fast. Professional. Masked. We couldn't ID them."
"Casualties?"
"Five of my guys. Broken bones. Gunshot wounds. All non-lethal."
Interesting.
"Anything else?"
"They knew what they were looking for. Went straight for the safe. Got it open in under a minute. This wasn't random."
No. It wasn't.
I lean back in my chair. Stare at the map.
"Find out who. Pull surveillance footage from the facility, nearby businesses, traffic cameras. I want faces. Names. Addresses."
"Yes, sir."
"And Marcus?"
"Sir?"
"Increase security on all storage locations. Double the patrols. If someone's targeting my operations, I want to know immediately."
"Understood."
I hang up.
Sit in silence.
Someone's hitting my network. Someone who knows what they're looking for. Someone professional.
This isn't street-level crime. This is surgical.
I pick up the phone. Dial a different number.
"We may have a problem. Someone's targeting operations. Find out who and make an example."
I hang up.
Stare at the map.
Twenty years of building this empire.
No one takes it from me.
No one.
